# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: antibody
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:antibody/11s-globulin-family] It is characterized by a hexamer (with hexagonal shape).
[src:antibody/11s-globulin-family] Several residues are conserved among 11S family.
[src:antibody/11s-globulin-family] Like other globulins, they are not completely digested and broken into amino acids and have the potential to bind to various proteins in the body and can exert effects independent of their amino acids constituents, even after consumption.
[src:antibody/11s-globulin-family] They tend to have high emulsifying effects.
[src:antibody/acute-toxicity] Acute toxicity is distinguished from chronic toxicity, which describes the adverse health effects from repeated exposures, often at lower levels, to a substance over a longer time period (months or years).
[src:antibody/acute-toxicity] It is widely considered unethical to use humans as test subjects for acute (or chronic) toxicity research.
[src:antibody/acute-toxicity] However, some information can be gained from investigating accidental human exposures (e.g., factory accidents).
[src:antibody/acute-toxicity] Otherwise, most acute toxicity data comes from animal testing or, more recently, *in vitro* testing methods and inference from data on similar substances.
[src:antibody/acute-toxicity] Limits for short-term exposure, such as STELs or CVs, are defined only if there is a particular acute toxicity associated with a substance.
[src:antibody/acute-toxicity] These limits are set by the American Conference of Governmental Industrial Hygienists (ACGIH) and the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA), based on experimental data.
[src:antibody/acute-toxicity] The values set by these organizations do not always coincide exactly, and in the chemical industry it is general practice to choose the most conservative value in order to ensure the safety of employees.
[src:antibody/acute-toxicity] The values can typically be found in a material safety data sheet.
[src:antibody/acute-toxicity] There are also different values based on the method of entry of the compound (oral, dermal, or inhalation).
[src:antibody/acute-toxicity] The most referenced value in the chemical industry is the median lethal dose, or LD50.
[src:antibody/acute-toxicity] This is the concentration of substance which resulted in the death of 50% of test subjects (typically mice or rats) in the laboratory.
[src:antibody/acute-toxicity] When a person has been exposed to an acutely toxic dose of a substance, they can be treated in a number of ways in order to minimize the harmful effects.
[src:antibody/acute-toxicity] The severity of the response is related to the severity of the toxic response exhibited.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The **adaptive immune system** (**AIS**), also known as the **acquired immune system** or **specific immune system**, is a subsystem of the immune system that is composed of specialized cells, organs, and processes that eliminate pathogens specifically.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired immune system is one of the two main immunity strategies found in vertebrates (the other being the innate immune system).
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Like the innate system, the adaptive immune system includes both humoral immunity components and cell-mediated immunity components and destroys invading pathogens.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Unlike the innate immune system, which is pre-programmed to react to common broad categories of pathogen, the adaptive immune system is highly specific to each particular pathogen the body has encountered.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Adaptive immunity creates immunological memory after an initial response to a specific pathogen, and leads to an enhanced response to future encounters with that pathogen.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Antibodies are a critical part of the adaptive immune system.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Adaptive immunity can provide long-lasting protection, sometimes for the person's entire lifetime.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] For example, someone who recovers from measles is now protected against measles for their lifetime; in other cases it does not provide lifetime protection, as with chickenpox.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] This process of adaptive immunity is the basis of vaccination.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The cells that carry out the adaptive immune response are white blood cells known as lymphocytes.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] B cells and T cells, two different types of lymphocytes, carry out the main activities: antibody responses, and cell-mediated immune response.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] In antibody responses, B cells are activated to secrete antibodies, which are proteins also known as immunoglobulins.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Antibodies travel through the bloodstream and bind to the foreign antigen causing it to inactivate, which does not allow the antigen to bind to the host.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Antigens are any substances that elicit the adaptive immune response.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Sometimes the adaptive system is unable to distinguish harmful from harmless foreign molecules; the effects of this may be hayfever, asthma, or any other allergy.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] In adaptive immunity, pathogen-specific receptors are "acquired" during the lifetime of the organism (whereas in innate immunity pathogen-specific receptors are already encoded in the genome).
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] This acquired response is called "adaptive" because it prepares the body's immune system for future challenges (though it can actually also be maladaptive when it results in allergies or autoimmunity).
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The system is highly adaptable because of two factors.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] First, somatic hypermutation is a process of accelerated random genetic mutations in the antibody-coding genes, which allows antibodies with novel specificity to be created.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Second, V(D)J recombination randomly selects one variable (V), one diversity (D), and one joining (J) region for genetic recombination and discards the rest, which produces a highly unique combination of antigen-receptor gene segments in each lymphocyte.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] This mechanism allows a small number of genetic segments to generate a vast number of different antigen receptors, which are then uniquely expressed on each individual lymphocyte.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Since the gene rearrangement leads to an irreversible change in the DNA of each cell, all progeny (offspring) of that cell inherit genes that encode the same receptor specificity, including the memory B cells and memory T cells that are the keys to long-lived specific immunity.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The term "adaptive" was first used by Robert Good in reference to antibody responses in frogs as a synonym for "acquired immune response" in 1964.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Good acknowledged he used the terms as synonyms but explained only that he preferred to use the term "adaptive".
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The term "adaptive" as used in immunology is problematic as acquired immune responses can be both adaptive and maladaptive in the physiological sense.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Indeed, both acquired and innate immune responses can be both adaptive and maladaptive in the evolutionary sense.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Most textbooks today, following the early use by Janeway, use "adaptive" almost exclusively and noting in glossaries that the term is synonymous with "acquired".
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The classic sense of "acquired immunity" came to mean, since Tonegawa's discovery, "antigen-specific immunity mediated by somatic gene rearrangements that create clone-defining antigen receptors".
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] In the last decade, the term "adaptive" has been increasingly applied to another class of immune response not so-far associated with somatic gene rearrangements.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] These include expansion of natural killer (NK) cells with so-far unexplained specificity for antigens, expansion of NK cells expressing germ-line encoded receptors, and activation of other innate immune cells to an activated state that confers a short-term "immune memory".
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] In this sense, "adaptive immunity" more closely resembles the concept of "activated state" or "heterostasis", thus returning in sense to the physiological sense of "adaptation" to environmental changes.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Acquired immunity is triggered in vertebrates when a pathogen evades the innate immune system and (1) generates a threshold level of antigen and (2) generates "stranger" or "danger" signals activating dendritic cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] In humans, it takes 4–7 days for the adaptive immune system to mount a significant response.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] T and B lymphocytes are the cells of the adaptive immune system.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The human body has about 2 trillion lymphocytes, which are 20–40% of white blood cells; their total mass is about the same as the brain or liver.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The peripheral bloodstream contains only 2% of all circulating lymphocytes; the other 98% move within tissues and the lymphatic system, which includes the lymph nodes and spleen.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] In humans, approximately 1–2% of the lymphocyte pool recirculates each hour to increase the opportunity for the cells to encounter the specific pathogen and antigen that they react to.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] B cells and T cells are derived from the same multipotent hematopoietic stem cells, and look identical to one another until after they are activated.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] B cells play a large role in the humoral immune response, whereas T cells are intimately involved in cell-mediated immune responses.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] In all vertebrates except Agnatha, B cells and T cells are produced by stem cells in the bone marrow.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] T cell progenitors then migrate from the bone marrow to the thymus, where they develop further.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Acquired immunity relies on the capacity of immune cells to distinguish between the body's own cells and unwanted invaders.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The host's cells express "self" antigens.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] These antigens are different from those on the surface of bacteria or on the surface of virus-infected host cells ("non-self" or "foreign" antigens).
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired immune response is triggered by recognizing foreign antigen in the cellular context of an activated dendritic cell.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] With the exception of non-nucleated cells (including erythrocytes), all cells are capable of presenting antigen through the function of major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Some cells are specially equipped to present antigen, and to prime naive T cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Dendritic cells, B-cells, and macrophages are equipped with special "co-stimulatory" ligands recognized by co-stimulatory receptors on T cells, and are termed professional antigen-presenting cells (APCs).
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Several T cells subgroups can be activated by professional APCs, and each type of T cell is specially equipped to deal with each unique toxin or microbial pathogen.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The type of T cell activated, and the type of response generated, depends, in part, on the context in which the APC first encountered the antigen.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Dendritic cells engulf exogenous pathogens, such as bacteria, parasites or toxins in the tissues and then migrate, via chemotactic signals, to the T cell-enriched lymph nodes.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] During migration, dendritic cells undergo a process of maturation in which they lose most of their ability to engulf other pathogens, and develop an ability to communicate with T-cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The dendritic cell uses enzymes to chop the pathogen into smaller pieces, called antigens.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] In the lymph node, the dendritic cell displays these non-self antigens on its surface by coupling them to a receptor called the major histocompatibility complex, or MHC (also known in humans as human leukocyte antigen (HLA)).
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] This MHC-antigen complex is recognized by T-cells passing through the lymph node.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Exogenous antigens are usually displayed on MHC class II molecules, which activate CD4+T helper cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Endogenous antigens are produced by intracellular bacteria and viruses replicating within a host cell.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The host cell uses enzymes to digest virally associated proteins and displays these pieces on its surface to T-cells by coupling them to MHC.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Endogenous antigens are typically displayed on MHC class I molecules, and activate CD8+ cytotoxic T-cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] With the exception of non-nucleated cells (including erythrocytes), MHC class I is expressed by all host cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Cytotoxic T cells (also known as TC, cytotoxic T-lymphocytes (CTLs), or killer T cells) are a sub-group of T cells that induce the death of cells that are infected with viruses (and other pathogens), or are otherwise damaged or dysfunctional.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Naive cytotoxic T cells are activated when their T-cell receptor (TCR) strongly interacts with a peptide-bound MHC class I molecule.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] This affinity depends on the type and orientation of the antigen/MHC complex, and is what keeps the CTL and infected cell bound together.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Once activated, the CTL undergoes a process called clonal selection, in which it gains functions and divides rapidly to produce an army of "armed" effector cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The activated CTL then travels throughout the body searching for cells that bear that unique MHC class I + peptide.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] When exposed to these infected or dysfunctional somatic cells, effector CTLs release perforin and granulysin: cytotoxins that form pores in the target cell's plasma membrane, allowing ions and water to flow into the infected cell and causing it to burst or lyse.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] CTLs release granzyme, a serine protease encapsulated in a granule that enters cells via pores to induce apoptosis (cell death).
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] To limit extensive tissue damage during an infection, CTL activation is tightly controlled and in general requires a very strong MHC/antigen activation signal, or additional activation signals provided by "helper" T-cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] On resolution of the infection, most effector cells die and phagocytes clear them away—but a few of these cells remain as memory cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] On a later encounter with the same antigen, these memory cells quickly differentiate into effector cells, dramatically shortening the time required to mount an effective response.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] CD4+ lymphocytes, also called "helper" T cells, are immune response mediators, and play an important role in establishing and maximizing the capabilities of the acquired immune response.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] These cells have no cytotoxic or phagocytic activity; and cannot kill infected cells or clear pathogens, but, in essence "manage" the immune response, by directing other cells to perform these tasks.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Helper T cells express T cell receptors (TCR) that recognize antigen bound to Class II MHC molecules.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The activation of a naive helper T-cell causes it to release cytokines, which influences the activity of many cell types, including the APC (Antigen-Presenting Cell) that activated it.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Helper T-cells require a much milder activation stimulus than cytotoxic T cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Helper T cells can provide extra signals that "help" activate cytotoxic cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Classically, two types of effector CD4+ T helper cell responses can be induced by a professional APC, designated Th1 and Th2, each designed to eliminate different types of pathogens.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The factors that dictate whether an infection triggers a Th1 or Th2 type response are not fully understood, but the response generated does play an important role in the clearance of different pathogens.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The Th1 response is characterized by the production of Interferon-gamma, which activates the bactericidal activities of macrophages, and induces B cells to make opsonizing (marking for phagocytosis) and complement-fixing antibodies, and leads to *cell-mediated immunity*.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] In general, Th1 responses are more effective against intracellular pathogens (viruses and bacteria that are inside host cells).
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The Th2 response is characterized by the release of Interleukin 5, which induces eosinophils in the clearance of parasites.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Th2 also produce Interleukin 4, which facilitates B cell isotype switching.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] In general, Th2 responses are more effective against extracellular bacteria, parasites including helminths and toxins.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Like cytotoxic T cells, most of the CD4+ helper cells die on resolution of infection, with a few remaining as CD4+ memory cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Increasingly, there is strong evidence from mouse and human-based scientific studies of a broader diversity in CD4+ effector T helper cell subsets.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Regulatory T (Treg) cells, have been identified as important negative regulators of adaptive immunity as they limit and suppress the immune system to control aberrant immune responses to self-antigens; an important mechanism in controlling the development of autoimmune diseases.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Follicular helper T (Tfh) cells are another distinct population of effector CD4+ T cells that develop from naive T cells post-antigen activation.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Tfh cells are specialized in helping B cell humoral immunity as they are uniquely capable of migrating to follicular B cells in secondary lymphoid organs and provide them positive paracrine signals to enable the generation and recall production of high-quality affinity-matured antibodies.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Similar to Tregs, Tfh cells also play a role in immunological tolerance as an abnormal expansion of Tfh cell numbers can lead to unrestricted autoreactive antibody production causing severe systemic autoimmune disorders.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The relevance of CD4+ T helper cells is highlighted during an HIV infection.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] HIV is able to subvert the immune system by specifically attacking the CD4+ T cells, precisely the cells that could drive the clearance of the virus, but also the cells that drive immunity against all other pathogens encountered during an organism's lifetime.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Gamma delta T cells (γδ T cells) possess an alternative T cell receptor (TCR) as opposed to CD4+ and CD8+ αβ T cells and share characteristics of helper T cells, cytotoxic T cells and natural killer cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Like other 'unconventional' T cell subsets bearing invariant TCRs, such as CD1d-restricted natural killer T cells, γδ T cells exhibit characteristics that place them at the border between innate and acquired immunity.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] On one hand, γδ T cells may be considered a component of adaptive immunity in that they rearrange TCR genes via V(D)J recombination, which also produces junctional diversity, and develop a memory phenotype.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] On the other hand, however, the various subsets may also be considered part of the innate immune system where a restricted TCR or NK receptors may be used as a pattern recognition receptor.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] For example, according to this paradigm, large numbers of Vγ9/Vδ2 T cells respond within hours to common molecules produced by microbes, and highly restricted intraepithelial Vδ1 T cells respond to stressed epithelial cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] B Cells are the major cells involved in the creation of antibodies that circulate in blood plasma and lymph, known as humoral immunity.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Antibodies (also known as immunoglobulin, Ig), are large Y-shaped proteins used by the immune system to identify and neutralize foreign objects.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] In mammals, there are five types of antibody: IgA, IgD, IgE, IgG, and IgM, differing in biological properties; each has evolved to handle different kinds of antigens.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Upon activation, B cells produce antibodies, each of which recognize a unique antigen, and neutralizing specific pathogens.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Like the T cell, B cells express a unique B cell receptor (BCR), in this case, a membrane-bound antibody molecule.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] All the BCR of any one clone of B cells recognizes and binds to only one particular antigen.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] A critical difference between B cells and T cells is how each cell "sees" an antigen.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] T cells recognize their cognate antigen in a processed form – as a peptide in the context of an MHC molecule, whereas B cells recognize antigens in their native form.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Once a B cell encounters its cognate (or specific) antigen (and receives additional signals from a helper T cell (predominately Th2 type)), it further differentiates into an effector cell, known as a plasma cell.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Plasma cells are short-lived cells (2–3 days) that secrete antibodies.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] These antibodies bind to antigens, making them easier targets for phagocytes, and trigger the complement cascade.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] About 10% of plasma cells survive to become long-lived antigen-specific memory B cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Already primed to produce specific antibodies, these cells can be called upon to respond quickly if the same pathogen re-infects the host, while the host experiences few, if any, symptoms.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Primitive jawless vertebrates, such as the lamprey and hagfish, have an adaptive immune system that shows 3 different cell lineages, each sharing a common origin with B cells, αβ T cells, and innate-like γΔ T cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Instead of the classical antibodies and T cell receptors, these animals possess a large array of molecules called variable lymphocyte receptors (VLRs for short) that, like the antigen receptors of jawed vertebrates, are produced from only a small number (one or two) of genes.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] These molecules are believed to bind pathogenic antigens in a similar way to antibodies, and with the same degree of specificity.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] For a long time it was thought that insects and other invertebrates possess only innate immune system.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] However, in recent years some of the basic hallmarks of adaptive immunity have been discovered in insects.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Those traits are immune memory and specificity.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Although the hallmarks are present the mechanisms are different from those in vertebrates.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Immune memory in insects was discovered through the phenomenon of priming.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] When insects are exposed to non-lethal dose or heat killed bacteria they are able to develop a memory of that infection that allows them to withstand otherwise lethal dose of the same bacteria they were exposed to before.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Unlike in vertebrates, insects do not possess cells specific for adaptive immunity.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Instead those mechanisms are mediated by hemocytes.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Hemocytes function similarly to phagocytes and after priming they are able to more effectively recognize and engulf the pathogen.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] It was also shown that it is possible to transfer the memory into offspring.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] For example, in honeybees if the queen is infected with bacteria then the newly born workers have enhanced abilities in fighting with the same bacteria.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Other experimental model based on red flour beetle also showed pathogen specific primed memory transfer into offspring from both mothers and fathers.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The most commonly accepted theory of this specificity is based on the *Dscam* gene.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The *Dscam* gene, which mediates phagocytosis in some insects, contains three variable Ig domains.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] These domains can be alternatively spliced, producing a large number of possible isoforms.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] It has been shown that after exposure to different pathogens, different isoforms of Dscam are produced, and that these isoforms associate and defend against bacteria in an isoform-specific manner.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Another mechanism that supports the specificity of insect immunity is RNA interference (RNAi).
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] RNAi is a form of antiviral immunity with high specificity.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] It has several different pathways that all end with the virus being unable to replicate.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] One of the pathways is siRNA in which long double stranded RNA is cut into pieces that serve as templates for protein complex Ago2-RISC that finds and degrades complementary RNA of the virus.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] MiRNA pathway in cytoplasm binds to Ago1-RISC complex and functions as a template for viral RNA degradation.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Last one is piRNA where small RNA binds to the Piwi protein family and controls transposones and other mobile elements.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Despite the research the exact mechanisms responsible for immune priming and specificity in insects are not well described.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] CRISPR has a lot of short repeated sequences.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] These sequences are part of an adaptive immune system for prokaryotes.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] It allows them to remember and counter the bacteriophages which prey on them.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] They work as a kind of acquired immune system for bacteria.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] When B cells and T cells are activated some become memory B cells and some memory T cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Throughout the lifetime of an animal these memory cells form a database of effective B and T lymphocytes.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Upon interaction with a previously encountered antigen, the appropriate memory cells are selected and activated.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] In this manner, the second and subsequent exposures to an antigen produce a stronger and faster immune response.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] This is "adaptive" in the sense that the body's immune system prepares itself for future challenges, but is "maladaptive" of course if the receptors are autoimmune.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Immunological memory can be in the form of either *passive* short-term memory or *active* long-term memory.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Passive memory is usually short-term, lasting between a few days and several months.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Newborn infants have had no prior exposure to microbes and are particularly vulnerable to infection.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Several layers of passive protection are provided by the mother.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] *In utero*, maternal IgG is transported directly across the placenta, so that, at birth, human babies have high levels of antibodies, with the same range of antigen specificities as their mother.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Breast milk contains antibodies (mainly IgA) that are transferred to the gut of the infant, protecting against bacterial infections, until the newborn can synthesize its own antibodies.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] This is passive immunity because the fetus does not actually make any memory cells or antibodies: It only borrows them.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Short-term passive immunity can also be transferred artificially from one individual to another via antibody-rich serum.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] In general, active immunity is long-term and can be acquired by infection followed by B cell and T cell activation, or artificially acquired by vaccines, in a process called immunization.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Historically, infectious disease has been the leading cause of death in the human population.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Over the last century, two important factors have been developed to combat their spread: sanitation and immunization.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Immunization (commonly referred to as vaccination) is the deliberate induction of an immune response, and represents the single most effective manipulation of the immune system that scientists have developed.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Immunizations are successful because they utilize the immune system's natural specificity as well as its inducibility.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The principle behind immunization is to introduce an antigen, derived from a disease-causing organism, that stimulates the immune system to develop protective immunity against that organism, but that does not itself cause the pathogenic effects of that organism.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] An antigen (short for *anti*body *gen*erator), is defined as any substance that binds to a specific antibody and elicits an adaptive immune response.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Most viral vaccines are based on live attenuated viruses, whereas many bacterial vaccines are based on acellular components of microorganisms, including harmless toxin components.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Many antigens derived from acellular vaccines do not strongly induce an adaptive response, and most bacterial vaccines require the addition of *adjuvants* that activate the antigen-presenting cells of the innate immune system to enhance immunogenicity.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Most large molecules, including virtually all proteins and many polysaccharides, can serve as antigens.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The parts of an antigen that interact with an antibody molecule or a lymphocyte receptor, are called epitopes, or antigenic determinants.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Most antigens contain a variety of epitopes and can stimulate the production of antibodies, specific T cell responses, or both.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] A very small proportion (less than 0.01%) of the total lymphocytes are able to bind to a particular antigen, which suggests that only a few cells respond to each antigen.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Even in the absence of antigen stimulation, a human can produce more than 1 trillion different antibody molecules.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Millions of genes would be required to store the genetic information that produces these receptors, but, the entire human genome contains fewer than 25,000 genes.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Myriad receptors are produced through a process known as clonal selection.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] According to the clonal selection theory, at birth, an animal randomly generates a vast diversity of lymphocytes (each bearing a unique antigen receptor) from information encoded in a small family of genes.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] To generate each unique antigen receptor, these genes have undergone a process called V(D)J recombination, or *combinatorial diversification*, in which one gene segment recombines with other gene segments to form a single unique gene.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] This assembly process generates the enormous diversity of receptors and antibodies, before the body ever encounters antigens, and enables the immune system to respond to an almost unlimited diversity of antigens.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Throughout an animal's lifetime, lymphocytes that can react against the antigens an animal actually encounters are selected for action—directed against anything that expresses that antigen.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The innate and acquired portions of the immune system work together, not in spite of each other.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired arm, B, and T cells could not function without the innate system input.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] T cells are useless without antigen-presenting cells to activate them, and B cells are disabled without T cell help.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] On the other hand, the innate system would likely be overrun with pathogens without the specialized action of the adaptive immune response.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The cornerstone of the immune system is the recognition of "self" versus "non-self".
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Therefore, the mechanisms that protect the human fetus (which is considered "non-self") from attack by the immune system, are particularly interesting.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Although no comprehensive explanation has emerged to explain this mysterious, and often repeated, lack of rejection, two classical reasons may explain how the fetus is tolerated.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The first is that the fetus occupies a portion of the body protected by a non-immunological barrier, the uterus, which the immune system does not routinely patrol.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The second is that the fetus itself may promote local immunosuppression in the mother, perhaps by a process of active nutrient depletion.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] A more modern explanation for this induction of tolerance is that specific glycoproteins expressed in the uterus during pregnancy suppress the uterine immune response (see eu-FEDS).
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] During pregnancy in viviparous mammals (all mammals except Monotremes), endogenous retroviruses (ERVs) are activated and produced in high quantities during the implantation of the embryo.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] They are currently known to possess immunosuppressive properties, suggesting a role in protecting the embryo from its mother's immune system.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The immunodepressive action was the initial normal behavior of the virus, similar to HIV.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The fusion proteins were a way to spread the infection to other cells by simply merging them with the infected one (HIV does this too).
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] It is believed that the ancestors of modern viviparous mammals evolved after an infection by this virus, enabling the fetus to survive the immune system of the mother.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The human genome project found several thousand ERVs classified into 24 families.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] This theory, which builds on the existing clonal selection hypothesis and since 1974 has been developed mainly by Niels Jerne and Geoffrey W.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Hoffmann, is seen as being relevant to the understanding of the HIV pathogenesis and the search for an HIV vaccine.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] One of the most interesting developments in biomedical science during the past few decades has been elucidation of mechanisms mediating innate immunity.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] One set of innate immune mechanisms is humoral, such as complement activation.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Another set comprises pattern recognition receptors such as toll-like receptors, which induce the production of interferons and other cytokines increasing resistance of cells such as monocytes to infections.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Cytokines produced during innate immune responses are among the activators of adaptive immune responses.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Antibodies exert additive or synergistic effects with mechanisms of innate immunity.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Unstable HbS clusters Band-3, a major integral red cell protein; antibodies recognize these clusters and accelerate their removal by phagocytic cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Clustered Band 3 proteins with attached antibodies activate complement, and complement C3 fragments are opsonins recognized by the CR1 complement receptor on phagocytic cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] A population study has shown that the protective effect of the sickle-cell trait against falciparum malaria involves the augmentation of acquired as well as innate immune responses to the malaria parasite, illustrating the expected transition from innate to acquired immunity.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Repeated malaria infections strengthen acquired immunity and broaden its effects against parasites expressing different surface antigens.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] By school age most children have developed efficacious adaptive immunity against malaria.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] These observations raise questions about mechanisms that favor the survival of most children in Africa while allowing some to develop potentially lethal infections.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] In malaria, as in other infections, innate immune responses lead into, and stimulate, adaptive immune responses.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The genetic control of innate and acquired immunity is now a large and flourishing discipline.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Humoral and cell-mediated immune responses limit malaria parasite multiplication, and many cytokines contribute to the pathogenesis of malaria as well as to the resolution of infections.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired immune system evolved as an elaboration of the innate immune system.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Lymphoid cells can be identified in some pre-vertebrate deuterostomes (i.e., sea urchins).
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The amphioxus is a chordate like all vertebrates.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Its genome includes many building blocks of the adaptive immune system, but none of the true hallmarks such as somatic recombination.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] There is, however, considerable expansion in LRR genes and immunoglobulin-fold genes.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] There is high polymorphism among different individuals, an example of diversity in the innate immune system.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired immune system, which has been best-studied in mammals, originated in jawed fish approximately 500 million years ago.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Most of the molecules, cells, tissues, and associated mechanisms of this system of defense are found in cartilaginous fishes.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Lymphocyte receptors, Ig and TCR, are found in all jawed vertebrates.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The most ancient Ig class, IgM, is membrane-bound and then secreted upon stimulation of cartilaginous fish B cells.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Another isotype, shark IgW, is related to mammalian IgD.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] TCRs, both α/β and γ/δ, are found in jawed fish (cladistically including mammals).
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Most elements of the jawed fish system are in place thanks to the second round of whole-genome duplication (2R) that the jawed fish have undergone, providing an expanded repertoire of immune-related genes.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The immunoprotease genes involved in antigen processing and presentation as well as the class I and class II genes, are closely linked within the MHC of almost all studied species.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] These systems, along with RAG, were set in place quickly after 2R had happened.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The MHC region is paralogous to the Ig/TCR region.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Comparing paralogous regions allow for the reconstruction of a *primordial immune complex*.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The cartilaginous fish system does have one critical difference compared to the system of bony fish (including mammals): the gene segments that undergo V(D)J recombination in bony fish are not organized in huge clusters like they are in bony fish.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Instead, these parts are arranged as "miniclusters" and rearrangement by RAG is largely limited within these clusters.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] As a result, not as many combinations are available compared to bony fish.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The RAG transposon likely invaded a "UrIg2" immunoglobin gene, which had an unsplit VJ, in an ancestor of all extant jawed fish.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Splitting the V and J exons is adaptive, as it enables greater variation through changing the size of the CDR3 loop.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] This feature is inherited by all the descendants of UrIg2 such as Ig and TCR.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The jawless fish are vertebrates like the jawed fish, but belong on a different branch.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] In jawless fish, three subsets of lymphocytes use variable lymphocyte receptors (VLRs) for antigen binding.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The VLRs are derived from pattern recognition receptors (PRRs) of the innate immune system.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Diversity is generated by a cytosine deaminase-mediated rearrangement of LRR-based DNA segments.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] The functional dichotomy between two of the lymphocyte subsets parallels Ig and TCR molecules.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Immunity can be acquired either actively or passively.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Immunity is acquired actively when a person is exposed to foreign substances and the immune system responds.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Passive immunity is when antibodies are transferred from one host to another.
[src:antibody/adaptive-immune-system] Both actively acquired and passively acquired immunity can be obtained by natural or artificial means.
[src:antibody/affimer] Affimer proteins were developed initially at the MRC Cancer Cell Unit in Cambridge then across two laboratories at the University of Leeds.
[src:antibody/affimer] Derived from the cysteine protease inhibitor family of cystatins, which function in nature as cysteine protease inhibitors, these 12–14 kDa proteins share the common tertiary structure of an alpha-helix lying on top of an anti-parallel beta-sheet.
[src:antibody/affimer] Affimer proteins display two peptide loops that can all be randomized to bind to desired target proteins, in a similar manner to monoclonal antibodies.
[src:antibody/affimer] Stabilization of the two peptides by the protein scaffold constrains the possible conformations that the peptides can take.
[src:antibody/affimer] This increases the binding affinity and specificity compared to libraries of free peptides, though can limit the target repertoire of Affimers.
[src:antibody/affimer] Phage display libraries of 109 randomized sequences are used to screen for Affimer proteins that exhibit high-specificity binding to the target protein with binding affinities in the nM range.
[src:antibody/affimer] The ability to direct *in vitro* screening techniques allows the identification of specific, high affinity Affimers.
[src:antibody/affimer] *In vitro* screening and development also mean that the target space for Affimers is not limited by the animal immune system.
[src:antibody/affimer] Affimers are generated using recombinant systems, so their generation is more rapid and reproducible compared to the production of polyclonal antibodies.
[src:antibody/affimer] Multimeric forms Affimers have been generated and shown to yield titres in the range of 200–400 mg/L under small-scale culture using bacterial host systems.
[src:antibody/affimer] Multimeric forms of Affimers with the same target specificity provide avidity effects in target binding.
[src:antibody/affimer] Many different tags and fusion proteins, such as fluorophores, single-stranded DNA, His, and c-Myc tags can be conjugated to Affimers.
[src:antibody/affimer] Specific cysteine residues can be introduced to the protein to allow thiol chemistry to uniformly orient Affimers on a solid support eg ELISA plates.
[src:antibody/affimer] This flexible functionalisation of the Affimer molecule allows functionality across multiple applications and assay formats.
[src:antibody/affimer] As they are manufactured using recombinant bacterial production processes, the batch-to-batch consistency for Affimers is improved compared to polyclonal antibodies, overcoming some of the issues of reproducibility and security of supply.
[src:antibody/affimer] These synthetic antibodies were engineered to be stable, non-toxic, biologically neutral and contain no post-translational modifications or disulfide bridges.
[src:antibody/affimer] Two separate loop sequences, incorporating a total of 12 to 36 amino acids, form the target interaction surface so interaction surfaces can range form 650–1000 Å.
[src:antibody/affimer] The large interaction surface results allows binding to target proteins.
[src:antibody/affimer] Affimer technology has been commercialised and developed by Avacta, which is developing these affinity reagents as tools for diagnostics and as biotherapeutics.
[src:antibody/affimer] Affimer binders have been used across a number of platforms, including ELISA, surface plasmon resonance, affinity purification.
[src:antibody/affimer] Affimers that inhibit protein-protein interactions can be produced with the potential to express these inhibitors in mammalian cells modify signalling pathways as cell therapies.
[src:antibody/affimer] The small size and stability profile of Affimers combined with their human origin confer drug-like properties.
[src:antibody/affimer] This may represent advantages over antibodies in terms of tissue penetration, for example in solid tumours where Avacta are developing PD-L1 inhibitors as alternatives to Opdivo and Yervoy, though requires half life modification to prevent rapid excretion through the kidney.
[src:antibody/affimer] Affimers can be conjugated to form multimers for the design of therapeutics.
[src:antibody/affimer] Examples include the production of multi-specific Affimer molecules to albumin binders to increase their half-life *in vivo* and for use as the targeting moiety in chimeric receptors or modified to carry a toxin in Affimer-drug conjugates.
[src:antibody/affimer] Affimers as therapeutics are in discovery and preclinical development to tackle cancer, both via CAR-T cell therapy and as checkpoint inhibitors.
[src:antibody/affimer] Early studies using *ex vivo* human samples showed low immunogenicity associated with the Affimer scaffold, at levels comparable to a marketed antibody therapeutic.
[src:antibody/affimer] Furthermore, initial preclinical studies showed good efficacy and tolerability of the anti-PDL1 immuno-oncology Affimers in mice.
[src:antibody/affimer] It is anticipated that IND filing for the first Affimer therapeutic will occur in 2023.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Affinity chromatography has the advantage of specific binding interactions between the analyte of interest (normally dissolved in the mobile phase), and a binding partner or ligand (immobilized on the stationary phase).
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] In a typical affinity chromatography experiment, the ligand is attached to a solid, insoluble matrix—usually a polymer such as agarose or polyacrylamide—chemically modified to introduce reactive functional groups with which the ligand can react, forming stable covalent bonds.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] The stationary phase is first loaded into a column to which the mobile phase is introduced.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Molecules that bind to the ligand will remain associated with the stationary phase.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] A wash buffer is then applied to remove non-target biomolecules by disrupting their weaker interactions with the stationary phase, while the biomolecules of interest will remain bound.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Target biomolecules may then be removed by applying a so-called elution buffer, which disrupts interactions between the bound target biomolecules and the ligand.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] The target molecule is thus recovered in the eluting solution.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Affinity chromatography does not require the molecular weight, charge, hydrophobicity, or other physical properties of the analyte of interest to be known, although knowledge of its binding properties is useful in the design of a separation protocol.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Types of binding interactions commonly exploited in affinity chromatography procedures are summarized in the table below.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Binding to the solid phase may be achieved by column chromatography whereby the solid medium is packed onto a column, the initial mixture run through the column to allow settling, a wash buffer run through the column and the elution buffer subsequently applied to the column and collected.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] These steps are usually done at ambient pressure.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Alternatively, binding may be achieved using a batch treatment, for example, by adding the initial mixture to the solid phase in a vessel, mixing, separating the solid phase, removing the liquid phase, washing, re-centrifuging, adding the elution buffer, re-centrifuging and removing the elute.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Sometimes a hybrid method is employed such that the binding is done by the batch method, but the solid phase with the target molecule bound is packed onto a column and washing and elution are done on the column.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] The ligands used in affinity chromatography are obtained from both organic and inorganic sources.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Examples of biological sources are serum proteins, lectins and antibodies.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Inorganic sources are moronic acid, metal chelates and triazine dyes.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] A third method, expanded bed absorption, which combines the advantages of the two methods mentioned above, has also been developed.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] The solid phase particles are placed in a column where liquid phase is pumped in from the bottom and exits at the top.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] The gravity of the particles ensure that the solid phase does not exit the column with the liquid phase.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Affinity columns can be eluted by changing salt concentrations, pH, pI, charge and ionic strength directly or through a gradient to resolve the particles of interest.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] More recently, setups employing more than one column in series have been developed.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] The advantage compared to single column setups is that the resin material can be fully loaded since non-binding product is directly passed on to a consecutive column with fresh column material.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] These chromatographic processes are known as periodic counter-current chromatography (PCC).
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] The resin costs per amount of produced product can thus be drastically reduced.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Since one column can always be eluted and regenerated while the other column is loaded, already two columns are sufficient to make full use of the advantages.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Additional columns can give additional flexibility for elution and regeneration times, at the cost of additional equipment and resin costs.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Affinity chromatography can be used in a number of applications, including nucleic acid purification, protein purification from cell free extracts, and purification from blood.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] By using affinity chromatography, one can separate proteins that bind to a certain fragment from proteins that do not bind that specific fragment.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Because this technique of purification relies on the biological properties of the protein needed, it is a useful technique and proteins can be purified many folds in one step.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Many different affinity media exist for a variety of possible uses.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Briefly, they are (generalized) activated/functionalized that work as a functional spacer, support matrix, and eliminates handling of toxic reagents.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Amino acid media is used with a variety of serum proteins, proteins, peptides, and enzymes, as well as rRNA and dsDNA.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Avidin biotin media is used in the purification process of biotin/avidin and their derivatives.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Carbohydrate bonding is most often used with glycoproteins or any other carbohydrate-containing substance; carbohydrate is used with lectins, glycoproteins, or any other carbohydrate metabolite protein.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Dye ligand media is nonspecific but mimics biological substrates and proteins.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Glutathione is useful for separation of GST tagged recombinant proteins.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Hydrophobic interaction media are most commonly used to target free carboxyl groups and proteins.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Nucleic acids function to trap mRNA, DNA, rRNA, and other nucleic acids/oligonucleotides.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Protein A/G method is used to purify immunoglobulins.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Speciality media are designed for a specific class or type of protein/co enzyme; this type of media will only work to separate a specific protein or coenzyme.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Another use for the procedure is the affinity purification of antibodies from blood serum.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] If the serum is known to contain antibodies against a specific antigen (for example if the serum comes from an organism immunized against the antigen concerned) then it can be used for the affinity purification of that antigen.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] This is also known as Immunoaffinity Chromatography.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] For example, if an organism is immunised against a GST-fusion protein it will produce antibodies against the fusion-protein, and possibly antibodies against the GST tag as well.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] The protein can then be covalently coupled to a solid support such as agarose and used as an affinity ligand in purifications of antibody from immune serum.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] For thoroughness, the GST protein and the GST-fusion protein can each be coupled separately.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] The serum is initially allowed to bind to the GST affinity matrix.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] This will remove antibodies against the GST part of the fusion protein.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] The serum is then separated from the solid support and allowed to bind to the GST-fusion protein matrix.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] This allows any antibodies that recognize the antigen to be captured on the solid support.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Elution of the antibodies of interest is most often achieved using a low pH buffer such as glycine pH 2.8.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] The eluate is collected into a neutral tris or phosphate buffer, to neutralize the low pH elution buffer and halt any degradation of the antibody's activity.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] This is a nice example as affinity purification is used to purify the initial GST-fusion protein, to remove the undesirable anti-GST antibodies from the serum and to purify the target antibody.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Monoclonal antibodies can also be selected to bind proteins with great specificity, where protein is released under fairly gentle conditions.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] This can become of use for further research in the future.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] A simplified strategy is often employed to purify antibodies generated against peptide antigens.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] When the peptide antigens are produced synthetically, a terminal cysteine residue is added at either the N- or C-terminus of the peptide.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] This cysteine residue contains a sulfhydryl functional group which allows the peptide to be easily conjugated to a carrier protein (e.g.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] The same cysteine-containing peptide is also immobilized onto an agarose resin through the cysteine residue and is then used to purify the antibody.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Most monoclonal antibodies have been purified using affinity chromatography based on immunoglobulin-specific Protein A or Protein G, derived from bacteria.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Immunoaffinity chromatography with monoclonal antibodies immobilized on monolithic column has been successfully used to capture extracellular vesicles (e.g., exosomes and exomeres) from human blood plasma by targeting tetraspanins and integrins found on the surface of the EVs.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Immunoaffinity chromatography is also the basis for immunochromatographic test (ICT) strips, which provide a rapid means of diagnosis in patient care.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Using ICT, a technician can make a determination at a patient's bedside, without the need for a laboratory.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] ICT detection is highly specific to the microbe causing an infection.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Immunoaffinity chromatography has been applied to the selective isolation of blood-derived components, including lymphocytes and specific proteins, using antibody-functionalized stationary phases.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Antibody-based detection methods are also used in forensic serology to identify blood and evaluate its persistence on substrates over time, demonstrating the broader role of immunological specificity in forensic body-fluid analysis.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Immobilized metal ion affinity chromatography (IMAC) is based on the specific coordinate covalent bond of amino acids, particularly histidine, to metals.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Many naturally occurring proteins do not have an affinity for metal ions, therefore recombinant DNA technology can be used to introduce such a protein tag into the relevant gene.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Methods used to elute the protein of interest include changing the pH, or adding a competitive molecule, such as imidazole.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Possibly the most common use of affinity chromatography is for the purification of recombinant proteins.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Proteins with a known affinity are protein tagged in order to aid their purification.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] The protein may have been genetically modified so as to allow it to be selected for affinity binding; this is known as a fusion protein.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Protein tags include hexahistidine (His), glutathione-S-transferase (GST), maltose binding protein (MBP), and the Colicin E7 variant CL7 tag.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Histidine tags have an affinity for nickel, cobalt, zinc, copper and iron ions which have been immobilized by forming coordinate covalent bonds with a chelator incorporated in the stationary phase.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] For elution, an excess amount of a compound able to act as a metal ion ligand, such as imidazole, is used.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] GST has an affinity for glutathione which is commercially available immobilized as glutathione agarose.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] During elution, excess glutathione is used to displace the tagged protein.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] CL7 has an affinity and specificity for Immunity Protein 7 (Im7) which is commercially available immobilized as Im7 agarose resin.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] For elution, an active and site-specific protease is applied to the Im7 resin to release the tag-free protein.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Lectin affinity chromatography is a form of affinity chromatography where lectins are used to separate components within the sample.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Lectins, such as concanavalin A are proteins which can bind specific alpha-D-mannose and alpha-D-glucose carbohydrate molecules.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Some common carbohydrate molecules that is used in lectin affinity chromatography are Con A-Sepharose and WGA-agarose.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Another example of a lectin is wheat germ agglutinin which binds D-N-acetyl-glucosamine.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] The most common application is to separate glycoproteins from non-glycosylated proteins, or one glycoform from another glycoform.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Although there are various ways to perform lectin affinity chromatography, the goal is extract a sugar ligand of the desired protein.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Another use for affinity chromatography is the purification of specific proteins using a gel matrix that is unique to a specific protein.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] This property allows the enzyme to bind to the stationary phase of the affinity matrix and β-Galactosidase is eluted by adding increasing concentrations of salt to the column.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Alkaline phosphatase from *E. coli* can be purified using a DEAE-Cellulose matrix.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] A. phosphatase has a slight negative charge, allowing it to weakly bind to the positively charged amine groups in the matrix.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] The enzyme can then be eluted out by adding buffer with higher salt concentrations.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Boronate affinity chromatography consists of using boronic acid or boronates to elute and quantify amounts of glycoproteins.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Clinical adaptations have applied this type of chromatography for use in determining long term assessment of diabetic patients through analysis of their glycated hemoglobin.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Affinity purification of albumin and macroglobulin contamination is helpful in removing excess albumin and α2-macroglobulin contamination, when performing mass spectrometry.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] In affinity purification of serum albumin, the stationary used for collecting or attracting serum proteins can be Cibacron Blue-Sepharose.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Then the serum proteins can be eluted from the adsorbent with a buffer containing thiocyanate (SCN−).
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] The WAC technology is demonstrated against a number of different protein targets – proteases, kinases, chaperones and protein–protein interaction (PPI) targets.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] WAC has been shown to be more effective than established methods for fragment based screening.
[src:antibody/affinity-chromatography] Affinity chromatography was conceived and first developed by Pedro Cuatrecasas and Meir Wilchek.
[src:antibody/affinity-maturation] In immunology, **affinity maturation** is the process by which TFH cell-activated B cells produce antibodies with increased affinity for antigen during the course of an immune response.
[src:antibody/affinity-maturation] With repeated exposures to the same antigen, a host will produce antibodies of successively greater affinities.
[src:antibody/affinity-maturation] A secondary response can elicit antibodies with several fold greater affinity than in a primary response.
[src:antibody/affinity-maturation] Affinity maturation primarily occurs on membrane immunoglobulin of germinal center B cells and as a direct result of somatic hypermutation (SHM) and selection by TFH cells.
[src:antibody/affinity-maturation] Clonal selection: B cells that have undergone SHM must compete for limiting growth resources, including the availability of antigen and paracrine signals from TFH cells.
[src:antibody/affinity-maturation] The follicular dendritic cells (FDCs) of the germinal centers present antigen to the B cells, and the B cell progeny with the highest affinities for antigen, having gained a competitive advantage, are favored for positive selection leading to their survival.
[src:antibody/affinity-maturation] Positive selection is based on steady cross-talk between TFH cells and their cognate antigen presenting GC B cell.
[src:antibody/affinity-maturation] Because a limited number of TFH cells reside in the germinal center, only highly competitive B cells stably conjugate with TFH cells and thus receive T cell-dependent survival signals.
[src:antibody/affinity-maturation] B cell progeny that have undergone SHM, but bind antigen with lower affinity will be out-competed, and be deleted.
[src:antibody/affinity-maturation] Over several rounds of selection, the resultant secreted antibodies produced will have effectively increased affinities for antigen.
[src:antibody/affinity-maturation] Like the natural prototype, the *in vitro* affinity maturation is based on the principles of mutation and selection.
[src:antibody/affinity-maturation] The *in vitro* affinity maturation has successfully been used to optimize antibodies, antibody fragments or other peptide molecules like antibody mimetics.
[src:antibody/affinity-maturation] Random mutations inside the CDRs are introduced using radiation, chemical mutagens or error-prone PCR.
[src:antibody/affinity-maturation] In addition, the genetic diversity can be increased by chain shuffling.
[src:antibody/affinity-maturation] Two or three rounds of mutation and selection using display methods like phage display usually results in antibody fragments with affinities in the low nanomolar range.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] In biochemistry and pharmacology, a **ligand** is a substance that forms a complex with a biomolecule to serve a biological purpose.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] The etymology stems from Latin *ligare*, which means 'to bind'.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] In protein-ligand binding, the ligand is usually a molecule which produces a signal by binding to a site on a target protein.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] The binding typically results in a change of conformational isomerism (conformation) of the target protein.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] In DNA-ligand binding studies, the ligand can be a small molecule, ion, or protein which binds to the DNA double helix.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] The relationship between ligand and binding partner is a function of charge, hydrophobicity, and molecular structure.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Binding occurs by intermolecular forces, such as ionic bonds, hydrogen bonds and Van der Waals forces.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] The association or docking is actually reversible through dissociation.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Measurably irreversible covalent bonding between a ligand and target molecule is atypical in biological systems.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] In contrast to the definition of ligand in metalorganic and inorganic chemistry, in biochemistry it is ambiguous whether the ligand generally binds at a metal site, as is the case in hemoglobin.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] In general, the interpretation of ligand is contextual with regard to what sort of binding has been observed.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Ligand binding to a receptor protein alters the conformation by affecting the three-dimensional shape orientation.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] The conformation of a receptor protein composes the functional state.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Ligands include substrates, inhibitors, activators, signaling lipids, and neurotransmitters.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] The rate of binding is called affinity, and this measurement typifies a tendency or strength of the effect.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Binding affinity is actualized not only by host–guest interactions, but also by solvent effects that can play a dominant, steric role which drives non-covalent binding in solution.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] The solvent provides a chemical environment for the ligand and receptor to adapt, and thus accept or reject each other as partners.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Radioligands are radioisotope labeled compounds used in vivo as tracers in PET studies and for in vitro binding studies.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] The interaction of ligands with their binding sites can be characterized in terms of a binding affinity.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] In general, high-affinity ligand binding results from greater attractive forces between the ligand and its receptor while low-affinity ligand binding involves less attractive force.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] In general, high-affinity binding results in a higher occupancy of the receptor by its ligand than is the case for low-affinity binding; the residence time (lifetime of the receptor-ligand complex) does not correlate.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] High-affinity binding of ligands to receptors is often physiologically important when some of the binding energy can be used to cause a conformational change in the receptor, resulting in altered behavior for example of an associated ion channel or enzyme.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] A ligand that can bind to and alter the function of the receptor that triggers a physiological response is called a receptor agonist.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Ligands that bind to a receptor but fail to activate the physiological response are receptor antagonists.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] High-affinity ligand binding implies that a relatively low concentration of a ligand is adequate to maximally occupy a ligand-binding site and trigger a physiological response.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Receptor affinity is measured by an inhibition constant or Ki value, the concentration required to occupy 50% of the receptor.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Ligand affinities are most often measured indirectly as an IC50 value from a competition binding experiment where the concentration of a ligand required to displace 50% of a fixed concentration of reference ligand is determined.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] The Ki value can be estimated from IC50 through the Cheng Prusoff equation.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Ligand affinities can also be measured directly as a dissociation constant (Kd) using methods such as fluorescence quenching, isothermal titration calorimetry or surface plasmon resonance.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Low-affinity binding (high Ki level) implies that a relatively high concentration of a ligand is required before the binding site is maximally occupied and the maximum physiological response to the ligand is achieved.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] In the example shown to the right, two different ligands bind to the same receptor binding site.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Only one of the agonists shown can maximally stimulate the receptor and, thus, can be defined as a *full agonist*.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] An agonist that can only partially activate the physiological response is called a *partial agonist*.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] In this example, the concentration at which the full agonist (red curve) can half-maximally activate the receptor is about 5 × 10−9 Molar (nM = nanomolar).
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Binding affinity is most commonly determined using a radiolabeled ligand, known as a tagged ligand.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] *Homologous competitive binding experiments* involve binding competition between a tagged ligand and an untagged ligand.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] MP-SPR also enables measurements in high saline dissociation buffers thanks to a unique optical setup.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Microscale thermophoresis (MST), an immobilization-free method was developed.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] This method allows the determination of the binding affinity without any limitation to the ligand's molecular weight.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] For the use of statistical mechanics in a quantitative study of the ligand-receptor binding affinity, see the comprehensive article on the configurational partition function.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Binding affinity data alone does not determine the overall potency of a drug or a naturally produced (biosynthesized) hormone.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Potency is a result of the complex interplay of both the binding affinity and the ligand efficacy.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Ligand efficacy refers to the ability of the ligand to produce a biological response upon binding to the target receptor and the quantitative magnitude of this response.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] This response may be as an agonist, antagonist, or inverse agonist, depending on the physiological response produced.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Selective ligands have a tendency to bind to very limited kinds of receptor, whereas non-selective ligands bind to several types of receptors.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] This plays an important role in pharmacology, where drugs that are non-selective tend to have more adverse effects, because they bind to several other receptors in addition to the one generating the desired effect.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] PIP2) in complex with a hydrophobic protein (e.g. lipid-gated ion channels) determining the affinity is complicated by non-specific hydrophobic interactions.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Non-specific hydrophobic interactions can be overcome when the affinity of the ligand is high.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] For example, PIP2 binds with high affinity to PIP2 gated ion channels.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Bivalent ligands consist of two drug-like molecules (pharmacophores or ligands) connected by an inert linker.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] There are various kinds of bivalent ligands and are often classified based on what the pharmacophores target.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Homobivalent ligands target two of the same receptor types.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Heterobivalent ligands target two different receptor types.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Bitopic ligands target an orthosteric binding sites and allosteric binding sites on the same receptor.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] In scientific research, bivalent ligands have been used to study receptor dimers and to investigate their properties.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] This class of ligands was pioneered by Philip S.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Portoghese and coworkers while studying the opioid receptor system.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Bivalent ligands were also reported early on by Micheal Conn and coworkers for the gonadotropin-releasing hormone receptor.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Since these early reports, there have been many bivalent ligands reported for various G protein-coupled receptor (GPCR) systems including cannabinoid, serotonin, oxytocin, and melanocortin receptor systems, and for GPCR-LIC systems (D2 and nACh receptors).
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Bivalent ligands usually tend to be larger than their monovalent counterparts, and therefore, not 'drug-like' as in Lipinski's rule of five.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Many believe this limits their applicability in clinical settings.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] In spite of these beliefs, there have been many ligands that have reported successful pre-clinical animal studies.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Given that some bivalent ligands can have many advantages compared to their monovalent counterparts (such as tissue selectivity, increased binding affinity, and increased potency or efficacy), bivalents may offer some clinical advantages as well.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Ligands of proteins can be characterized also by the number of protein chains they bind.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] "Monodesmic" ligands (μόνος: single, δεσμός: binding) are ligands that bind a single protein chain, while "polydesmic" ligands (πολοί: many) are frequent in protein complexes, and are ligands that bind more than one protein chain, typically in or near protein interfaces.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Recent research shows that the type of ligands and binding site structure has profound consequences for the evolution, function, allostery and folding of protein compexes.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] A privileged scaffold is a molecular framework or chemical moiety that is statistically recurrent among known drugs or among a specific array of biologically active compounds.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] These privileged elements can be used as a basis for designing new active biological compounds or compound libraries.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] The dramatically increased computing power of supercomputers and personal computers has made it possible to study protein–ligand interactions also by means of computational chemistry.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] For example, a worldwide grid of well over a million ordinary PCs was harnessed for cancer research in the project grid.org, which ended in April 2007.
[src:antibody/affinity-pharmacology] Grid.org has been succeeded by similar projects such as World Community Grid, Human Proteome Folding Project, Compute Against Cancer and Folding@Home.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] An **antibody** (**Ab**), or **immunoglobulin** (**Ig**), is a large protein belonging to the immunoglobulin superfamily which is used by the immune system to identify and neutralize antigens such as those that exist on bacteria and virus cells, including those that cause disease.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Each individual antibody recognizes one or more specific antigens, and antigens (a portmanteau of "antibody generator") of virtually any size and chemical composition can be recognized.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Each of the branching chains comprising the "Y" of an antibody contains a paratope (the antigen-binding site) that specifically binds to one particular epitope (a specific part of an antigen bound by the paratope) on an antigen, allowing the two molecules to bind together with precision.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Using this mechanism, antibodies can effectively "tag" the antigen (or a microbe or an infected cell bearing such an antigen) for attack by cells of the immune system, or can neutralize it directly (for example, by blocking a part of a virus that is essential for its ability to invade a host cell).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Antibodies may be borne on the surface of an immune cell, as in a B cell receptor, or they may exist freely by being secreted into the extracellular space.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The term *antibody* generally refers to the free (secreted) form, while the term *immunoglobulin* can refer to either forms.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Since they are, broadly speaking, the same protein, the terms are often treated as synonymous.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] To allow the immune system to recognize millions of different antigens, the antigen-binding paratopes at each tip of the antibody come in an equally wide variety.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The rest of an antibody's structure is much less variable; in humans, antibodies occur in five classes or isotypes: IgA, IgD, IgE, IgG, and IgM.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Human IgG and IgA antibodies are also divided into discrete subclasses (IgG1, IgG2, IgG3, and IgG4; IgA1 and IgA2).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The class refers to the functions triggered by the antibody (also known as effector functions), in addition to some other structural features.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Antibodies from different classes also differ in where they are released in the body and at what stage of an immune response.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Between species, while classes and subclasses of antibodies may be shared (at least in name), their function and distribution throughout the body may be different, which complicates the use of animal models in studying antibodies.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] For example, mouse IgG1 is closer to human IgG2 than to human IgG1 in terms of its function.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In general, antibodies are considered part of the adaptive immune system, though this classification can become complicated.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] For example, natural IgM, which are made by B-1 cells that have properties more similar to innate immune cells than adaptive, refers to IgM antibodies made independently of an immune response that demonstrate polyreactivity—i.e. they recognize multiple distinct (unrelated) antigens.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] These can work with the complement system in the earliest phases of an immune response to help facilitate clearance of the offending antigen and delivery of the resulting immune complexes to the lymph nodes or spleen for initiation of an immune response.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Hence in this capacity, the functions of antibodies are more akin to that of innate immunity than adaptive.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Antibodies arise from antibody-secreting cells, a term that encompasses plasmablasts and plasma cells.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In the course of an immune response, B cells can progressively differentiate into antibody-secreting cells or into memory B cells.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Plasmablasts and plasma cells differ mainly in the degree to which they secrete antibodies, their lifespan, metabolic adaptations, and surface markers.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Plasmablasts are rapidly proliferating, short-lived cells produced in the early phases of the immune response (classically described as arising from extrafollicular reactions rather than from a germinal center) which have the potential to differentiate further into plasma cells.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Occasionally plasmablasts are mis-described as short-lived plasma cells; formally this is incorrect because plasma cells do not divide (they are terminally differentiated), and rely on survival niches comprising specific cell types and cytokines to persist.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] It is commonly said that plasma cells do not express surface immunoglobulin (whereas plasmablasts do), but this depends on the class of antibody that the plasma cell generates (IgG-secreting plasma cells do not, but IgM, IgA, and IgE plasma cells do).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Plasma cells will secrete huge quantities of antibody regardless of whether or not antigen is present, ensuring that antibody levels to the antigen in question do not fall to zero, provided the plasma cell stays alive.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The rate of antibody secretion, however, can be regulated, for example, by the presence of adjuvant molecules that stimulate the immune response such as toll-like receptor ligands.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Long-lived plasma cells can live for potentially the entire lifetime of the organism.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Classically, the survival niches that house long-lived plasma cells reside in the bone marrow, though it cannot be assumed that any given plasma cell in the bone marrow will be long-lived.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] However, other work indicates that survival niches can readily be established within the mucosal tissues, though the classes of antibodies involved show a different hierarchy from those in the bone marrow.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] B cells can also differentiate into memory B cells which can persist for decades, similarly to long-lived plasma cells.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] These cells can be rapidly recalled in a secondary immune response, undergoing class switching, affinity maturation, and differentiating into antibody-secreting cells.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Antibodies are heavy (~150 kDa) proteins of about 10 nm in size, arranged in three globular regions that roughly form a Y shape.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In humans and most other mammals, an antibody unit consists of four polypeptide chains; two identical *heavy chains* and two identical *light chains* connected by disulfide bonds.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Each chain is a series of domains: somewhat similar sequences of about 110 amino acids each.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] These domains are usually represented in simplified schematics as rectangles.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Light chains consist of one variable domain VL and one constant domain CL, while heavy chains contain one variable domain VH and three to four constant domains CH1, CH2, ...
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Structurally an antibody is also partitioned into two antigen-binding fragments (Fab), containing one VL, VH, CL, and CH1 domain each, as well as the crystallisable fragment (Fc), forming the trunk of the Y shape.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In between them is a hinge region of the heavy chains, whose flexibility allows antibodies to bind to pairs of epitopes at various distances, to form complexes (dimers, trimers, etc.), and to bind effector molecules more easily.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In an electrophoresis test of blood proteins, antibodies mostly migrate to the last, gamma globulin fraction.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Conversely, most gamma-globulins are antibodies, which is why the two terms were historically used as synonyms, as were the symbols Ig and γ.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] This variant terminology fell out of use due to the correspondence being inexact and due to confusion with γ (gamma) heavy chains which characterize the IgG class of antibodies.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The variable domains can also be referred to as the FV region.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] It is the subregion of Fab that binds to an antigen.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] More specifically, each variable domain contains three *hypervariable regions* – the amino acids seen there vary the most from antibody to antibody.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] When the protein folds, these regions give rise to three loops of β-strands, localized near one another on the surface of the antibody.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] These loops are referred to as the complementarity-determining regions (CDRs), since their shape complements that of an antigen.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Three CDRs from each of the heavy and light chains together form an antibody-binding site whose shape can be anything from a pocket to which a smaller antigen binds, to a larger surface, to a protrusion that sticks out into a groove in an antigen.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Typically though, only a few residues contribute to most of the binding energy.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The structures of CDRs have been clustered and classified by Chothia et al. and more recently by North et al. and Nikoloudis et al.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] However, describing an antibody's binding site using only one single static structure limits the understanding and characterization of the antibody's function and properties.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] To improve antibody structure prediction and to take the strongly correlated CDR loop and interface movements into account, antibody paratopes should be described as interconverting states in solution with varying probabilities.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In the framework of the immune network theory, CDRs are also called idiotypes.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] According to immune network theory, the adaptive immune system is regulated by interactions between idiotypes.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The Fc region (the trunk of the Y shape) is composed of constant domains from the heavy chains.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Its role is in modulating immune cell activity: it is where effector molecules bind to, triggering various effects after the antibody Fab region binds to an antigen.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Effector cells (such as macrophages or natural killer cells) bind via their Fc receptors (FcR) to the Fc region of an antibody, while the complement system is activated by binding the C1q protein complex (also via the Fc region).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] IgG or IgM can bind to C1q, but IgA cannot, therefore IgA does not activate the classical complement pathway.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Another role of the Fc region is to selectively distribute different antibody classes across the body.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In particular, the neonatal Fc receptor (FcRn) binds to the Fc region of IgG antibodies to transport it across the placenta, from the mother to the fetus.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In addition to this, binding to FcRn endows IgG with an exceptionally long half-life relative to other plasma proteins of 3–4 weeks.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] IgG3 in most cases (depending on allotype) has mutations at the FcRn binding site which lower affinity for FcRn, which are thought to have evolved to limit the highly inflammatory effects of this subclass.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Antibodies are glycoproteins, that is, they have carbohydrates (glycans) added to conserved amino acid residues.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] These conserved glycosylation sites occur in the Fc region and influence interactions with effector molecules.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The N-terminus of each chain is situated at the tip.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Each immunoglobulin domain has a similar structure, characteristic of all the members of the immunoglobulin superfamily: it is composed of between 7 (for constant domains) and 9 (for variable domains) β-strands, forming two beta sheets in a Greek key motif.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The sheets create a "sandwich" shape, the immunoglobulin fold, held together by a disulfide bond.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Secreted antibodies can occur as a single Y-shaped unit, a monomer.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] However, some antibody classes also form dimers with two Ig units (as with IgA), tetramers with four Ig units (like teleost fish IgM), or pentamers with five Ig units (like shark IgW or mammalian IgM, which occasionally forms hexamers as well, with six units).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] IgG can also form hexamers, though no J chain is required.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] IgA tetramers and pentamers have also been reported.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Antibodies also form complexes by binding to antigen: this is called an antigen-antibody complex or *immune complex*.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Small antigens can cross-link two antibodies, also leading to the formation of antibody dimers, trimers, tetramers, etc.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Multivalent antigens (e.g., cells with multiple epitopes) can form larger complexes with antibodies.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] An extreme example is the clumping, or agglutination, of red blood cells with antibodies in blood typing to determine blood groups: the large clumps become insoluble, leading to visually apparent precipitation.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The membrane-bound form of an antibody may be called a *surface immunoglobulin* (sIg) or a *membrane immunoglobulin* (mIg).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] It is part of the *B cell receptor* (BCR), which allows a B cell to detect when a specific antigen is present in the body and triggers B cell activation.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The BCR is composed of surface-bound IgD or IgM antibodies and associated Ig-α and Ig-β heterodimers, which are capable of signal transduction.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] A typical human B cell will have 50,000 to 100,000 antibodies bound to its surface.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Upon antigen binding, they cluster in large patches, which can exceed 1 micrometer in diameter, on lipid rafts that isolate the BCRs from most other cell signaling receptors.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] These patches may improve the efficiency of the cellular immune response.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In humans, the cell surface is bare around the B cell receptors for several hundred nanometers, which further isolates the BCRs from competing influences.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Antibodies can come in different varieties known as *isotypes* or *classes*.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In humans there are five antibody classes known as IgA, IgD, IgE, IgG, and IgM, which are further subdivided into subclasses such as IgA1, IgA2.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The prefix "Ig" stands for *immunoglobulin*, while the suffix denotes the type of heavy chain the antibody contains: the heavy chain types α (alpha), γ (gamma), δ (delta), ε (epsilon), μ (mu) give rise to IgA, IgG, IgD, IgE, IgM, respectively.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The distinctive features of each class are determined by the part of the heavy chain within the hinge and Fc region.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The classes differ in their biological properties, functional locations and ability to deal with different antigens, as depicted in the table.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] For example, IgE antibodies are responsible for an allergic response consisting of histamine release from mast cells, often a sole contributor to asthma (though other pathways exist as do symptoms very similar to yet not technically asthma).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The variable region of these antibodies bind to allergic antigen, for example house dust mite particles, while its Fc region (in the ε heavy chains) binds to Fc receptor ε on a mast cell, triggering its degranulation: the release of molecules stored in its granules.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The antibody isotype of a B cell changes during cell development and activation.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Immature B cells, which have never been exposed to an antigen, express only the IgM isotype in a cell surface bound form.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The B lymphocyte, in this ready-to-respond form, is known as a "naive B lymphocyte." The naive B lymphocyte expresses both surface IgM and IgD.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The co-expression of both of these immunoglobulin isotypes renders the B cell ready to respond to antigen.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] B cell activation follows engagement of the cell-bound antibody molecule with an antigen, causing the cell to divide and differentiate into an antibody-producing cell called a plasma cell.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] This requires cytokines from T helper cells, unless antigen cross-links B cell receptors.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In this activated form, the B cell starts to produce antibody in a secreted form rather than a membrane-bound form.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Activated B cells that encounter certain signaling molecules undergo immunoglobulin class switching, also known as isotype switching, which causes the production of antibodies to change from IgM or IgD to the other antibody isotypes, IgE, IgA, or IgG.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In mammals there are two types of immunoglobulin light chain, which are called lambda (λ) and kappa (κ).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] However, there is no known functional difference between them, and both can occur with any of the five major types of heavy chains.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Each antibody contains two identical light chains: both κ or both λ.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Proportions of κ and λ types vary by species and can be used to detect abnormal proliferation of B cell clones.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Other types of light chains, such as the iota (ι) chain, are found in other vertebrates like sharks (Chondrichthyes) and bony fishes (Teleostei).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Though there is no known functional significance to the different choice of light chain class, the ratio of light chains can be diagnostically useful.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] For example, humans normally have a ratio of 2:1 of κ:λ light chains, and significant deviation from this ratio can indicate the presence of a monoclonal gammopathy (in which there is a proliferation of a plasma cell which may or may not be pre-malignant or malignant).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In most placental mammals, the structure of antibodies is generally similar.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Jawed fish appear to be the most primitive animals that are able to make antibodies similar to those of mammals, although many features of their adaptive immunity appeared somewhat earlier.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Cartilaginous fish (such as sharks) produce heavy-chain-only antibodies (i.e., lacking light chains) which moreover feature longer chain pentamers (with five constant units per molecule).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Camelids (such as camels, llamas, alpacas) are also notable for producing heavy-chain-only antibodies.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The antibody's paratope interacts with the antigen's epitope.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] An antigen usually contains different epitopes along its surface arranged discontinuously, and dominant epitopes on a given antigen are called determinants.Antibody and antigen interact by spatial complementarity (lock and key).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The molecular forces involved in the Fab-epitope interaction are weak and non-specific – for example electrostatic forces, hydrogen bonds, hydrophobic interactions, and van der Waals forces.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] This means binding between antibody and antigen is reversible, and the antibody's affinity towards an antigen is relative rather than absolute.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Relatively weak binding also means it is possible for an antibody to cross-react with different antigens of different relative affinities.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] More indirectly, an antibody can signal immune cells to present antibody fragments to T cells, or downregulate other immune cells to avoid autoimmunity.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] At the prenatal and neonatal stages of life, the presence of antibodies is provided by passive immunity from the mother through transplacental transfer of IgG antibodies and breastmilk antibodies (predominantly secretory IgA in humans).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] There are also important species-specific differences in the structure of the placenta, which complicates interpretations of how placental transfer of antibody works in humans.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Early endogenous antibody production varies for different kinds of antibodies, and usually appear within the first years of life.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Since antibodies exist freely in the bloodstream, they are said to be part of the humoral immune system.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Circulating antibodies (other than natural IgM) are produced by clonal B cells that specifically respond to only one antigen (unless the antibodies recognize an epitope with structural similarity across many different antigens).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Antibodies will also trigger vasoactive amine degranulation to contribute to immunity against certain types of antigens (helminths, allergens).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Antibodies that bind to surface antigens (for example, on bacteria) will attract the first component of the complement cascade with their Fc region and initiate activation of the "classical" complement system.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] This results in the killing of bacteria in two ways.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] First, the binding of the antibody and complement molecules marks the microbe for ingestion by phagocytes in a process called opsonization; these phagocytes are attracted by certain complement molecules generated in the complement cascade.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Second, some complement system components form a membrane attack complex to assist antibodies to kill the bacterium directly (bacteriolysis).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] To combat pathogens that replicate outside cells, antibodies bind to pathogens to link them together, causing them to agglutinate.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Since an antibody has at least two paratopes, it can bind more than one antigen by binding identical epitopes carried on the surfaces of these antigens.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] By coating the pathogen, antibodies stimulate effector functions against the pathogen in cells that recognize their Fc region.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Those cells that recognize coated pathogens have Fc receptors, which, as the name suggests, interact with the Fc region of IgA, IgG, and IgE antibodies.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The activation of natural killer cells by antibodies initiates a cytotoxic mechanism known as antibody-dependent cell-mediated cytotoxicity (ADCC) – this process may explain the efficacy of monoclonal antibodies used in biological therapies against cancer.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The Fc receptors are isotype-specific, which gives greater flexibility to the immune system, invoking only the appropriate immune mechanisms for distinct pathogens.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Humans and higher primates also produce "natural antibodies" that are present in serum before viral infection.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Natural antibodies have been defined as antibodies that are produced without any previous infection, vaccination, other foreign antigen exposure or passive immunization.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] These antibodies can activate the classical complement pathway leading to lysis of enveloped virus particles long before the adaptive immune response is activated.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Antibodies are produced exclusively by B cells in response to antigens where initially, antibodies are formed as membrane-bound receptors, but upon activation by antigens and helper T cells, B cells differentiate to produce soluble antibodies.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Many natural antibodies are directed against the disaccharide galactose α(1,3)-galactose (α-Gal), which is found as a terminal sugar on glycosylated cell surface proteins, and generated in response to production of this sugar by bacteria contained in the human gut.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] These antibodies undergo quality checks in the endoplasmic reticulum (ER), which contains proteins that assist in proper folding and assembly.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Rejection of xenotransplantated organs is thought to be, in part, the result of natural antibodies circulating in the serum of the recipient binding to α-Gal antigens expressed on the donor tissue.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Antibodies are central to the immune protection elicited by most vaccines (although other components of the immune system certainly participate and for some diseases are considerably more important than antibodies in generating an immune response, such as in the case of shingles).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] At the same time, many microbes of medical importance have the ability to mutate to escape antibodies elicited by prior infections, and long-lived plasma cells cannot undergo affinity maturation or class switching.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] This is compensated for through memory B cells: novel variants of a microbe that still retain structural features of previously encountered antigens can elicit memory B cell responses that adapt to those changes.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] It has been suggested that long-lived plasma cells secrete B cell receptors with higher affinity than those on the surfaces of memory B cells, but findings are not entirely consistent on this point.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Virtually all microbes can trigger an antibody response.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Successful recognition and eradication of many different types of microbes requires diversity among antibodies; their amino acid composition varies allowing them to interact with many different antigens.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] It has been estimated that humans generate about 10 billion different antibodies, each capable of binding a distinct epitope of an antigen.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Although a huge repertoire of different antibodies is generated in a single individual, the number of genes available to make these proteins is limited by the size of the human genome.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Several complex genetic mechanisms have evolved that allow vertebrate B cells to generate a diverse pool of antibodies from a relatively small number of antibody genes.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] One of these domains is called the variable domain, which is present in each heavy and light chain of every antibody, but can differ in different antibodies generated from distinct B cells.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Differences between the variable domains are located on three loops known as hypervariable regions (HV-1, HV-2 and HV-3) or complementarity-determining regions (CDR1, CDR2 and CDR3).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] CDRs are supported within the variable domains by conserved framework regions.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The heavy chain locus contains about 65 different variable domain genes that all differ in their CDRs.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Combining these genes with an array of genes for other domains of the antibody generates a large cavalry of antibodies with a high degree of variability.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] This combination is called V(D)J recombination and discussed below.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Somatic recombination of immunoglobulins, also known as *V(D)J recombination*, involves the generation of a unique immunoglobulin variable region.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The variable region of each immunoglobulin heavy or light chain is encoded in several pieces—known as gene segments (subgenes).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] These segments are called variable (V), diversity (D) and joining (J) segments.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] V, D and J segments are found in Ig heavy chains, but only V and J segments are found in Ig light chains.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Multiple copies of the V, D and J gene segments exist, and are tandemly arranged in the genomes of mammals.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In the bone marrow, each developing B cell will assemble an immunoglobulin variable region by randomly selecting and combining one V, one D and one J gene segment (or one V and one J segment in the light chain).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] As there are multiple copies of each type of gene segment, and different combinations of gene segments can be used to generate each immunoglobulin variable region, this process generates a huge number of antibodies, each with different paratopes, and thus different antigen specificities.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The rearrangement of several subgenes (i.e.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] V2 family) for lambda light chain immunoglobulin is coupled with the activation of microRNA miR-650, which further influences biology of B-cells.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] RAG proteins play an important role with V(D)J recombination in cutting DNA at a particular region.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Without the presence of these proteins, V(D)J recombination would not occur.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] After a B cell produces a functional immunoglobulin gene during V(D)J recombination, it cannot express any other variable region (a process known as allelic exclusion) thus each B cell can produce antibodies containing only one kind of variable chain.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Following activation with antigen, B cells begin to proliferate rapidly.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In these rapidly dividing cells, the genes encoding the variable domains of the heavy and light chains undergo a high rate of point mutation, by a process called *somatic hypermutation* (SHM).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] SHM results in approximately one nucleotide change per variable gene, per cell division.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] As a consequence, any daughter B cells will acquire slight amino acid differences in the variable domains of their antibody chains.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] This serves to increase the diversity of the antibody pool and impacts the antibody's antigen-binding affinity.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Some point mutations will result in the production of antibodies that have a weaker interaction (low affinity) with their antigen than the original antibody, and some mutations will generate antibodies with a stronger interaction (high affinity).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] B cells that express high affinity antibodies on their surface will receive a strong survival signal during interactions with other cells, whereas those with low affinity antibodies will not, and will die by apoptosis.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Thus, B cells expressing antibodies with a higher affinity for the antigen will outcompete those with weaker affinities for function and survival allowing the average affinity of antibodies to increase over time.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The process of generating antibodies with increased binding affinities is called *affinity maturation*.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Affinity maturation occurs in mature B cells after V(D)J recombination, and is dependent on help from helper T cells.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Isotype or class switching is a biological process occurring after activation of the B cell, which allows the cell to produce different classes of antibody (IgA, IgE, or IgG).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The different classes of antibody, and thus effector functions, are defined by the constant (C) regions of the immunoglobulin heavy chain.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Initially, naive B cells express only cell-surface IgM and IgD with identical antigen binding regions.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Each isotype is adapted for a distinct function; therefore, after activation, an antibody with an IgG, IgA, or IgE effector function might be required to effectively eliminate an antigen.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Class switching allows different daughter cells from the same activated B cell to produce antibodies of different isotypes.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Only the constant region of the antibody heavy chain changes during class switching; the variable regions, and therefore antigen specificity, remain unchanged.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Thus the progeny of a single B cell can produce antibodies, all specific for the same antigen, but with the ability to produce the effector function appropriate for each antigenic challenge.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Class switching is triggered by cytokines; the isotype generated depends on which cytokines are present in the B cell environment.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Class switching occurs in the heavy chain gene locus by a mechanism called class switch recombination (CSR).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] This mechanism relies on conserved nucleotide motifs, called *switch (S) regions*, found in DNA upstream of each constant region gene (except in the δ-chain).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The DNA strand is broken by the activity of a series of enzymes at two selected S-regions.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The variable domain exon is rejoined through a process called non-homologous end joining (NHEJ) to the desired constant region (γ, α or ε).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] This process results in an immunoglobulin gene that encodes an antibody of a different isotype.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] An antibody can be called *monospecific* if it has specificity for a single antigen or epitope, or bispecific if it has affinity for two different antigens or two different epitopes on the same antigen.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] A group of antibodies can be called *polyvalent* (or *unspecific*) if they have affinity for various antigens or microorganisms.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Intravenous immunoglobulin, if not otherwise noted, consists of a variety of different IgG (polyclonal IgG).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In contrast, monoclonal antibodies are identical antibodies produced by a single B cell.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Heterodimeric antibodies, which are also asymmetrical antibodies, allow for greater flexibility and new formats for attaching a variety of drugs to the antibody arms.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] One of the general formats for a heterodimeric antibody is the "knobs-into-holes" format.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] This format is specific to the heavy chain part of the constant region in antibodies.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The "knobs" part is engineered by replacing a small amino acid with a larger one.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] It fits into the "hole", which is engineered by replacing a large amino acid with a smaller one.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] What connects the "knobs" to the "holes" are the disulfide bonds between each chain.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The "knobs-into-holes" shape facilitates antibody dependent cell mediated cytotoxicity.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Single-chain variable fragments (scFv) are connected to the variable domain of the heavy and light chain via a short linker peptide.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The linker is rich in glycine, which gives it more flexibility, and serine/threonine, which gives it specificity.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Two different scFv fragments can be connected together, via a hinge region, to the constant domain of the heavy chain or the constant domain of the light chain.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] This gives the antibody bispecificity, allowing for the binding specificities of two different antigens.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The "knobs-into-holes" format enhances heterodimer formation but does not suppress homodimer formation.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] To further improve the function of heterodimeric antibodies, many scientists are looking towards artificial constructs.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Artificial antibodies are largely diverse protein motifs that use the functional strategy of the antibody molecule, but are not limited by the loop and framework structural constraints of the natural antibody.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Controlling the combinational design of the sequence and the resulting three-dimensional space could enhance the natural design and allow for the attachment of different combinations of drugs to the arms.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Heterodimeric antibodies have a greater range in shapes they can take and the drugs that are attached to the arms do not have to be the same on each arm, allowing for different combinations of drugs to be used in cancer treatment.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Pharmaceuticals are able to produce highly functional bispecific, and even multispecific, antibodies.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The degree to which they can function is impressive given that such a change of shape from the natural form should lead to decreased functionality.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Antibody diversification typically occurs through somatic hypermutation, class switching, and affinity maturation targeting the BCR gene loci, but on occasion more unconventional forms of diversification have been documented.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] For example, in the case of malaria caused by *Plasmodium falciparum,* some antibodies from those who had been infected demonstrated an insertion from chromosome 19 containing a 98-amino acid stretch from leukocyte-associated immunoglobulin-like receptor 1, LAIR1, in the elbow joint.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] This represents a form of interchromosomal transposition.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] LAIR1 normally binds collagen, but can recognize repetitive interspersed families of polypeptides (RIFIN) family members that are highly expressed on the surface of *P. falciparum*-infected red blood cells.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In fact, these antibodies underwent affinity maturation that enhanced affinity for RIFIN but abolished affinity for collagen.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] These "LAIR1-containing" antibodies have been found in 5-10% of donors from Tanzania and Mali, though not in European donors.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] European donors did show 100-1000 nucleotide stretches inside the elbow joints as well, however.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] This particular phenomenon may be specific to malaria, as infection is known to induce genomic instability.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The first use of the term "antibody" occurred in a text by Paul Ehrlich.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The term *Antikörper* (the German word for *antibody*) appears in the conclusion of his article "Experimental Studies on Immunity", published in October 1891, which states that, "if two substances give rise to two different *Antikörper*, then they themselves must be different".
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] However, the term was not accepted immediately and several other terms for antibody were proposed; these included *Immunkörper*, *Amboceptor*, *Zwischenkörper*, *substance sensibilisatrice*, *copula*, *Desmon*, *philocytase*, *fixateur*, and *Immunisin*.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The word *antibody* has formal analogy to the word *antitoxin* and a similar concept to *Immunkörper* (*immune body* in English).
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] As such, the original construction of the word contains a logical flaw; the antitoxin is something directed against a toxin, while the antibody is a body directed against something.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The study of antibodies began in 1890 when Emil von Behring and Kitasato Shibasaburō described antibody activity against diphtheria and tetanus toxins.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Von Behring and Kitasato put forward the theory of humoral immunity, proposing that a mediator in serum could react with a foreign antigen.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Other researchers believed that antibodies existed freely in the blood and, in 1904, Almroth Wright suggested that soluble antibodies coated bacteria to label them for phagocytosis and killing; a process that he named opsoninization.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In the 1920s, Michael Heidelberger and Oswald Avery observed that antigens could be precipitated by antibodies and went on to show that antibodies are made of protein.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The biochemical properties of antigen-antibody-binding interactions were examined in more detail in the late 1930s by John Marrack.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The next major advance was in the 1940s, when Linus Pauling confirmed the lock-and-key theory proposed by Ehrlich by showing that the interactions between antibodies and antigens depend more on their shape than their chemical composition.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In 1948, Astrid Fagraeus discovered that B cells, in the form of plasma cells, were responsible for generating antibodies.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Further work concentrated on characterizing the structures of the antibody proteins.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] A major advance in these structural studies was the discovery in the early 1960s by Gerald Edelman and Joseph Gally of the antibody light chain, and their realization that this protein is the same as the Bence-Jones protein described in 1845 by Henry Bence Jones.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Edelman went on to discover that antibodies are composed of disulfide bond-linked heavy and light chains.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Around the same time, antibody-binding (Fab) and antibody tail (Fc) regions of IgG were characterized by Rodney Porter.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Together, these scientists deduced the structure and complete amino acid sequence of IgG, a feat for which they were jointly awarded the 1972 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] The Fv fragment was prepared and characterized by David Givol.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] While most of these early studies focused on IgM and IgG, other immunoglobulin isotypes were identified in the 1960s: Thomas Tomasi discovered secretory antibody (IgA); David S.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] Fahey discovered IgD; and Kimishige Ishizaka and Teruko Ishizaka discovered IgE and showed it was a class of antibodies involved in allergic reactions.
[src:antibody/antibody-p01] In a landmark series of experiments beginning in 1976, Susumu Tonegawa showed that genetic material can rearrange itself to form the vast array of available antibodies.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Detection of particular antibodies is a very common form of medical diagnostics, and applications such as serology depend on these methods.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] For example, in biochemical assays for disease diagnosis, a titer of antibodies directed against Epstein–Barr virus or Lyme disease is estimated from the blood.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] If those antibodies are not present, either the person is not infected or the infection occurred a *very* long time ago, and the B cells generating these specific antibodies have naturally decayed.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] In clinical immunology, levels of individual classes of immunoglobulins are measured by nephelometry (or turbidimetry) to characterize the antibody profile of patient.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Elevations in different classes of immunoglobulins are sometimes useful in determining the cause of liver damage in patients for whom the diagnosis is unclear.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] For example, IgM levels are often elevated in patients with primary biliary cirrhosis, whereas IgA deposition along hepatic sinusoids can suggest alcoholic liver disease.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Autoimmune disorders can often be traced to antibodies that bind the body's own epitopes; many can be detected through blood tests.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Antibodies directed against red blood cell surface antigens in immune mediated hemolytic anemia are detected with the Coombs test.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] The Coombs test is also used for antibody screening in blood transfusion preparation and also for antibody screening in antenatal women.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] New dioxaborolane chemistry enables radioactive fluoride (18F) labeling of antibodies, which allows for positron emission tomography (PET) imaging of cancer.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Targeted monoclonal antibody therapy is employed to treat diseases such as rheumatoid arthritis, multiple sclerosis, psoriasis, and many forms of cancer including non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, colorectal cancer, head and neck cancer and breast cancer.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Some immune deficiencies, such as X-linked agammaglobulinemia and hypogammaglobulinemia, result in partial or complete lack of antibodies.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] These diseases are often treated by inducing a short-term form of immunity called passive immunity.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Passive immunity is achieved through the transfer of ready-made antibodies in the form of human or animal serum, pooled immunoglobulin or monoclonal antibodies, into the affected individual.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Rh factor, also known as Rh D antigen, is an antigen found on red blood cells; individuals that are Rh-positive (Rh+) have this antigen on their red blood cells and individuals that are Rh-negative (Rh–) do not.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] During normal childbirth, delivery trauma or complications during pregnancy, blood from a fetus can enter the mother's system.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] In the case of an Rh-incompatible mother and child, consequential blood mixing may sensitize an Rh- mother to the Rh antigen on the blood cells of the Rh+ child, putting the remainder of the pregnancy, and any subsequent pregnancies, at risk for hemolytic disease of the newborn.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Rho(D) immune globulin antibodies are specific for human RhD antigen.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Anti-RhD antibodies are administered as part of a prenatal treatment regimen to prevent sensitization that may occur when a Rh-negative mother has a Rh-positive fetus.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Treatment of a mother with Anti-RhD antibodies prior to and immediately after trauma and delivery destroys Rh antigen in the mother's system from the fetus.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] This occurs before the antigen can stimulate maternal B cells to "remember" Rh antigen by generating memory B cells.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Therefore, her humoral immune system will not make anti-Rh antibodies, and will not attack the Rh antigens of the current or subsequent babies.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Rho(D) Immune Globulin treatment prevents sensitization that can lead to Rh disease, but does not prevent or treat the underlying disease itself.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Specific antibodies are produced by injecting an antigen into a mammal, such as a mouse, rat, rabbit, goat, sheep, horse, or human for large quantities of antibody.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Blood isolated from these animals contains *polyclonal antibodies*—multiple antibodies that bind to the same antigen—in the serum, which can now be called antiserum.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] (For medical products, the horse and the human are most commonly used: the former for its large blood volume and high antibody titers, the latter for a higher compatibility with other humans.) Antigens are also injected into chickens for generation of polyclonal antibodies in egg yolk.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] To obtain antibody that is specific for a single epitope of an antigen, antibody-secreting lymphocytes are isolated from the animal and immortalized by fusing them with a cancer cell line.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] The fused cells are called hybridomas, and will continually grow and secrete antibody in culture.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Single hybridoma cells are isolated by dilution cloning to generate cell clones that all produce the same antibody; these antibodies are called *monoclonal antibodies*.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Polyclonal and monoclonal antibodies are often purified using Protein A/G or antigen-affinity chromatography.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] In research, purified antibodies are used in many applications.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Antibodies for research applications can be found directly from antibody suppliers, or through use of a specialist search engine.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Research antibodies are most commonly used to identify and locate intracellular and extracellular proteins.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Antibodies are used in flow cytometry to differentiate cell types by the proteins they express; different types of cells express different combinations of cluster of differentiation molecules on their surface, and produce different intracellular and secretable proteins.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Proteins can also be detected and quantified with antibodies, using ELISA and ELISpot techniques.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Multiple attempts have been made to improve both the way that researchers validate antibodies and ways in which they report on antibodies.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Researchers using antibodies in their work need to record them correctly in order to allow their research to be reproducible (and therefore tested, and qualified by other researchers).
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Less than half of research antibodies referenced in academic papers can be easily identified.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Papers published in F1000 in 2014 and 2015 provide researchers with a guide for reporting research antibody use.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] The RRID paper, is co-published in 4 journals that implemented the RRIDs Standard for research resource citation, which draws data from the antibodyregistry.org as the source of antibody identifiers (see also group at Force11).
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Antibody regions can be used to further biomedical research by acting as a guide for drugs to reach their target.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Antibodies and Fc‑based constructs provide highly specific binding to cell-surface receptors and are used as targeting moieties in antibody–drug conjugates (ADCs), bispecifics, and Fc‑fusion drugs for cancer and other diseases.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] There are several ways to obtain antibodies, including *in vivo* techniques like animal immunization and various *in vitro* approaches, such as the phage display method.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Traditionally, most antibodies are produced by hybridoma cell lines through immortalization of antibody-producing cells by chemically induced fusion with myeloma cells.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] In some cases, additional fusions with other lines have created "triomas" and "quadromas".
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] The manufacturing process should be appropriately described and validated.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] The importance of antibodies in health care and the biotechnology industry demands knowledge of their structures at high resolution.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] This information is used for protein engineering, modifying the antigen binding affinity, and identifying an epitope, of a given antibody.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] X-ray crystallography is one commonly used method for determining antibody structures.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] However, crystallizing an antibody is often laborious and time-consuming.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Computational approaches provide a cheaper and faster alternative to crystallography, but their results are more equivocal, since they do not produce empirical structures.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Online web servers such as *Web Antibody Modeling* (WAM) and *Prediction of Immunoglobulin Structure* (PIGS) enable computational modeling of antibody variable regions.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] The ability to describe the antibody through binding affinity to the antigen is supplemented by information on antibody structure and amino acid sequences for the purpose of patent claims.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Several methods have been presented for computational design of antibodies based on the structural bioinformatics studies of antibody CDRs.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] There are a variety of methods used to sequence an antibody including Edman degradation, cDNA, etc.; albeit one of the most common modern uses for peptide/protein identification is liquid chromatography coupled with tandem mass spectrometry (LC-MS/MS).
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] High volume antibody sequencing methods require computational approaches for the data analysis, including de novo sequencing directly from tandem mass spectra and database search methods that use existing protein sequence databases.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Many versions of shotgun protein sequencing are able to increase the coverage by utilizing CID/HCD/ETD fragmentation methods and other techniques, and they have achieved substantial progress in attempt to fully sequence proteins, especially antibodies.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Other methods have assumed the existence of similar proteins, a known genome sequence, or combined top-down and bottom up approaches.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Current technologies have the ability to assemble protein sequences with high accuracy by integrating de novo sequencing peptides, intensity, and positional confidence scores from database and homology searches.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Antibody mimetics are organic compounds, like antibodies, that can specifically bind antigens.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] They consist of artificial peptides or proteins, or aptamer-based nucleic acid molecules with a molar mass of about 3 to 20 kDa.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Antibody fragments, such as Fab and nanobodies are not considered as antibody mimetics.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Common advantages over antibodies are better solubility, tissue penetration, stability towards heat and enzymes, and comparatively low production costs.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] Antibody mimetics have been developed and commercialized as research, diagnostic and therapeutic agents.
[src:antibody/antibody-p02] BAU (binding antibody unit, often as BAU/mL) is a measurement unit defined by the WHO for the comparison of assays detecting the same class of immunoglobulins with the same specificity.
